<DOC><DOCNO> AP890807-0102 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-89 1853EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Korea     08-07 0347</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Korea,0361</SECOND><HEAD>Students Attack Intelligence Agency, U.S. Center</HEAD><BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A small band of anti-governmentstudents attacked the headquarters of the national intelligenceagency Monday with firebombs and demanded it be closed down.   In Taegu, several hundred students hurled rocks and shatteredwindows at guardposts at the U.S. Cultural Center Sunday night andclashed with riot police, according to the Yonhap news agency.   The attack on the U.S. facility followed a rally at KyongbukUniversity to protest what some students said is governmentsuppression of a new teachers' union. Six students were arrested,but no injuries were reported.   On Monday ten students hurled firebombs into the compound of theAgency for National Security Planning in eastern Seoul, Yonhapreported.   ``Disband NSP'' the students shouted, according to the newsagency. It said the students painted slogans on the compound wallsbefore fleeing.   Police reported two demonstrators were arrested..   Kim Dae-jung, leader of the opposition Party for Peace andDemocracy, said Monday that ``anti-democratic forces within theruling party are threatening democracy.''   He said a crackdown on dissidents, the investigation of threepeople for making visits to communist North Korea and his detentionby the national security agency has given ``an anti-democraticfaction within the ruling camp'' more power.   ``Politics by the security agency'' threatens to stem thenation's move toward democracy, he said, and the ``faction thatfavored reforms has become weak.''   Kim was detained by the intelligence agency for 22 hours lastweek for questioning in connection with an illegal trip to NorthKorea by a lawmaker in his party.   Kim said his party, as the leading opposition party, had beensingled out for harrassment by intelligence agents.   President Roh Tae-woo, in a nationwide radio address Monday,urged radical students, a small but active minority on universitycampuses, to end violent protests. The radical students have littlepopular support because of their violent tactics.   Roh said ``the reckless acts of a small number of radicalleftists are deepening distrust and confrontation and obstructingreunification with the north.''</TEXT></DOC>